What is Socket Programming?

Socket Programming is a way of connecting two nodes (programs) on a network to communicate with each other.

One program acts as a Server, which listens for requests.

Another acts as a Client, which sends requests and receives responses.

It allows data exchange between systems over TCP/IP or UDP protocols.

ğŸ”— Key Concepts
Term	Description
Socket	Endpoint for communication between two machines.
IP Address	Unique identifier for a device on the network.
Port Number	Identifies a specific service or application on a device.
ServerSocket (Java Class)	Used on the server side to listen for and accept incoming connections.
Socket (Java Class)	Used on both sides for sending and receiving data once a connection is established.
TCP	Connection-oriented protocol ensuring reliable data transfer.
UDP	Connectionless protocol allowing fast, lightweight communication without reliability.

ğŸ–¥ï¸ Types of Socket Communication

TCP (Stream-based communication)

  Reliable and ordered data transmission.

  Classes used:

  ServerSocket (Server)

  Socket (Client)

UDP (Datagram-based communication)

  Connectionless and faster, but less reliable.

  Classes used:

  DatagramSocket

  DatagramPacket


How TCP Socket Communication Works
Steps:

Server side: 
  Create a ServerSocket on a specific port.

  Wait for client requests using accept().

  Communicate via input/output streams.

Client side:

  Create a Socket specifying the server IP and port.

  Send data using OutputStream.

  Receive data using InputStream.

Close the connection once communication is complete.


Flow of Execution

  Run Server.java first â†’ It starts listening on port 5000.

  Run Client.java â†’ It connects to the server.

  Exchange messages between client and server.

  Both programs terminate gracefully.


Advantages of Socket Programming

âœ… Real-time communication between processes.
âœ… Reliable data transfer using TCP.
âœ… Works over local networks or the internet.
âœ… Can be used for building chat applications, file transfer systems, etc.


What is a Port?

A port is a virtual communication endpoint that helps identify a specific process or service running on a machine.
It works together with the IP address to uniquely identify where data should go.

Think of it like:

ğŸ  IP address = house number,
ğŸšª Port number = door number leading to a specific room or service.

âš™ï¸ Port 5000 in Your Code
ServerSocket serverSocket = new ServerSocket(5000);


This means your server program is listening for client requests on port number 5000.

When a client program connects, it must use the same port number, like this:

Socket socket = new Socket("localhost", 5000);


If the client uses a different port, the server wonâ€™t recognize the connection request.

ğŸŒ Port Number Range
Range	Description
0 â€“ 1023	Well-known (reserved) ports â€” used by standard services like HTTP (80), HTTPS (443), FTP (21), etc.
1024 â€“ 49151	Registered ports â€” used by user applications and services.
49152 â€“ 65535	Dynamic/private ports â€” often used temporarily by the system.

Since 5000 is above 1024, itâ€™s a safe user-defined port, perfect for testing socket programs.

ğŸ“¡ Example in Context

Server Side: Opens door 5000 and waits.

Client Side: Knocks on door 5000 to establish a connection.

Once connected, both can send and receive messages.

ğŸ§  Tips:

Always ensure the port is free (not used by another program).

Avoid using reserved ports (0â€“1023).

Both client and server must use the same port for the connection.

âœ… In short:

Port 5000 is just a communication channel number where your server listens and your client connects.
You can replace 5000 with any other free port, e.g., 8080, 9000, etc.
